/* KCNA content - Kubernetes Fundamentals (44% of exam). Auto-generated. */
KCNA.register({"id": "fundamentals", "name": "Kubernetes Fundamentals", "weight": 44, "notes": [{"id": "fundamentals-note-1", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers and images (OCI, image layers, registries, runtimes)", "title": "Containers, Images, OCI and Runtimes", "html": "<p>Containers package an application plus its dependencies into a portable, isolated unit; images are the immutable templates they run from.</p><ul><li><strong>Containers</strong> share the host kernel and isolate using Linux <strong>namespaces</strong> (isolation) and <strong>cgroups</strong> (resource limits). They are lighter-weight than VMs (no guest OS).</li><li>An <strong>image</strong> is a read-only template; a <strong>container</strong> is a running instance with a thin writable layer on top.</li><li><strong>Image layers</strong>: images are built in stacked, read-only layers (one per build instruction). Layers are <strong>cached and shared</strong> across images, saving space and speeding builds/pulls.</li><li><strong>OCI (Open Container Initiative)</strong>: a CNCF-related standards body defining the <strong>image-spec</strong> (image format), <strong>runtime-spec</strong> (how to run containers), and <strong>distribution-spec</strong> (registry API). Ensures portability across tools.</li><li><strong>Registries</strong> store and distribute images (e.g., Docker Hub, GHCR, Quay, ECR). Images are referenced as <code>registry/repo:tag</code>; <strong>digests</strong> (sha256) pin exact content.</li><li><strong>Container runtimes</strong>: <strong>high-level</strong> runtimes like <strong>containerd</strong> and <strong>CRI-O</strong> manage image pull, storage, and lifecycle and implement the <strong>CRI (Container Runtime Interface)</strong>. <strong>Low-level</strong> runtime <strong>runc</strong> actually creates the container per the OCI runtime-spec.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Docker is no longer the cluster runtime; <strong>dockershim was removed</strong> in Kubernetes 1.24. Kubelet talks to runtimes via the <strong>CRI</strong>.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> OCI = image + runtime + distribution specs; CRI = how kubelet calls the runtime.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-2", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and the pod lifecycle", "title": "Pods and the Pod Lifecycle", "html": "<p>A <strong>Pod</strong> is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes and the basic unit of scheduling.</p><ul><li>A Pod wraps <strong>one or more containers</strong> that share a <strong>network namespace</strong> (same IP and port space, reachable via <code>localhost</code>) and can share <strong>storage volumes</strong>.</li><li>Pods are <strong>ephemeral</strong>: they are not healed in place. If a node dies, controllers create <strong>new</strong> Pods rather than reviving old ones.</li><li>Each Pod gets its own <strong>unique IP</strong>. Containers in a Pod are always scheduled together on the same node.</li><li><strong>Init containers</strong> run to completion, in order, before app containers start (setup tasks). <strong>Sidecar</strong> containers run alongside the main container (logging, proxy).</li></ul><p><strong>Pod phases</strong> (<code>status.phase</code>):</p><ul><li><strong>Pending</strong>: accepted but not all containers running (e.g., pulling image, awaiting scheduling).</li><li><strong>Running</strong>: bound to a node, at least one container running.</li><li><strong>Succeeded</strong>: all containers exited 0 and won't restart.</li><li><strong>Failed</strong>: all containers terminated, at least one failed.</li><li><strong>Unknown</strong>: state can't be determined (often node comms lost).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Probes</strong>: <strong>liveness</strong> (restart if unhealthy), <strong>readiness</strong> (remove from Service endpoints until ready), <strong>startup</strong> (protects slow-starting apps).</li><li><strong>restartPolicy</strong>: <code>Always</code> (default), <code>OnFailure</code>, <code>Never</code>.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> You rarely create bare Pods directly; use controllers (Deployment, Job, etc.) for self-healing.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-3", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and rolling updates", "title": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and Rolling Updates", "html": "<p>Deployments provide declarative, self-healing management of stateless Pods and handle versioned updates.</p><ul><li>A <strong>ReplicaSet</strong> ensures a specified <strong>number of replica Pods</strong> are running, using a label selector. It replaces failed/deleted Pods to maintain the desired count.</li><li>A <strong>Deployment</strong> manages ReplicaSets and adds <strong>rolling updates</strong> and <strong>rollbacks</strong>. You usually manage Deployments, not ReplicaSets directly.</li><li>On an update (e.g., new image), the Deployment creates a <strong>new ReplicaSet</strong> and gradually scales it up while scaling the old one down.</li></ul><p><strong>Update strategies</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>RollingUpdate</strong> (default): incremental replacement with zero downtime. Controlled by <code>maxSurge</code> (extra Pods allowed) and <code>maxUnavailable</code> (Pods that can be down).</li><li><strong>Recreate</strong>: terminates all old Pods, then creates new ones (causes downtime).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Rollback</strong>: <code>kubectl rollout undo deployment/&lt;name&gt;</code> reverts to a previous ReplicaSet. Check progress with <code>kubectl rollout status</code>.</li><li>Scale with <code>kubectl scale</code> or by editing <code>replicas</code>.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Deployment → manages ReplicaSet → manages Pods. ReplicaSet handles count; Deployment handles version rollout/rollback.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Deployments are for <strong>stateless</strong> apps; use StatefulSets for stateful ones.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-4", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services and basic networking (ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer, cluster DNS)", "title": "Services, Service Types and Cluster DNS", "html": "<p>A <strong>Service</strong> provides a stable network endpoint and load-balances traffic across a changing set of Pods selected by labels.</p><ul><li>Pods are ephemeral with changing IPs; a Service gives a <strong>stable virtual IP (ClusterIP)</strong> and DNS name in front of them.</li><li>Services use a <strong>label selector</strong> to find backing Pods, tracked as <strong>Endpoints / EndpointSlices</strong>.</li></ul><p><strong>Service types</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>ClusterIP</strong> (default): internal-only virtual IP, reachable inside the cluster.</li><li><strong>NodePort</strong>: exposes the Service on a static port (range <strong>30000-32767</strong>) on every node's IP; builds on ClusterIP.</li><li><strong>LoadBalancer</strong>: provisions an external cloud load balancer; builds on NodePort. Typical for cloud external access.</li><li><strong>ExternalName</strong>: maps the Service to an external DNS name via a CNAME (no proxying).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Cluster DNS</strong> (CoreDNS): gives Services DNS names like <code>service.namespace.svc.cluster.local</code>. Pods resolve Services by name automatically.</li><li><strong>Ingress</strong> manages external HTTP/HTTPS routing (host/path rules) to Services; needs an <strong>Ingress controller</strong>. Newer <strong>Gateway API</strong> is its successor.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> LoadBalancer ⊃ NodePort ⊃ ClusterIP (each builds on the previous).</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> CoreDNS is the default cluster DNS; the <strong>CNI</strong> plugin implements pod networking, not Services.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-5", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "title": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "html": "<p><strong>ConfigMaps</strong> and <strong>Secrets</strong> decouple configuration and sensitive data from container images, following the config-from-environment principle.</p><ul><li><strong>ConfigMap</strong>: stores <strong>non-confidential</strong> key/value configuration data (settings, config files, URLs).</li><li><strong>Secret</strong>: stores <strong>sensitive</strong> data (passwords, tokens, keys, TLS certs). Same idea as ConfigMaps but for secrets.</li></ul><p><strong>How they're consumed by Pods</strong>:</p><ul><li>As <strong>environment variables</strong> (individual keys or all keys via <code>envFrom</code>).</li><li>As <strong>mounted volume files</strong> (each key becomes a file).</li></ul><p><strong>Key facts about Secrets</strong>:</p><ul><li>Secret data is <strong>base64-encoded, NOT encrypted</strong> by default. Base64 is encoding, not security.</li><li>Secrets are stored in <strong>etcd</strong>; enable <strong>encryption at rest</strong> for real protection.</li><li>Use <strong>RBAC</strong> to limit who can read Secrets.</li><li>Secret types include <code>Opaque</code> (default), <code>kubernetes.io/tls</code>, and <code>kubernetes.io/dockerconfigjson</code> (image pull).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> The exam loves asking that Secrets are <strong>only base64-encoded by default</strong> — not encrypted unless encryption at rest is configured.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Both can be injected as env vars or files; both are namespaced objects.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-6", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces, labels, selectors and annotations", "title": "Namespaces, Labels, Selectors and Annotations", "html": "<p>These mechanisms organize, group, and identify objects within a cluster.</p><ul><li><strong>Namespaces</strong>: provide <strong>logical isolation</strong> and grouping of resources within one cluster (e.g., teams, environments). They scope names and enable <strong>resource quotas</strong> and <strong>RBAC</strong> boundaries.</li><li>Default namespaces: <code>default</code>, <code>kube-system</code> (control-plane components), <code>kube-public</code>, <code>kube-node-lease</code>.</li><li>Not everything is namespaced: <strong>Nodes</strong>, <strong>PersistentVolumes</strong>, and Namespaces themselves are <strong>cluster-scoped</strong>.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Labels</strong>: key/value pairs <strong>attached to objects</strong> for <strong>identification and grouping</strong>. They are meaningful to users and used by selectors (e.g., <code>app=web</code>, <code>env=prod</code>).</li><li><strong>Selectors</strong>: query objects by their labels. <strong>Equality-based</strong> (<code>=</code>, <code>!=</code>) and <strong>set-based</strong> (<code>in</code>, <code>notin</code>, <code>exists</code>). Services, Deployments, and ReplicaSets use selectors to find their Pods.</li><li><strong>Annotations</strong>: key/value pairs for <strong>non-identifying metadata</strong> (build info, tooling config, descriptions). <strong>Not used by selectors</strong>; can hold larger/structured data.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Labels are for <strong>selecting/grouping</strong>; annotations are for <strong>arbitrary metadata that tools read</strong>, never for selection.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Namespaces give isolation but are <strong>not a strong security boundary</strong> by themselves; pair with RBAC, quotas, and network policies.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-7", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control plane components (kube-apiserver, etcd, kube-scheduler, controller-manager, cloud-controller-manager)", "title": "Control Plane Components", "html": "<p>The <strong>control plane</strong> makes global decisions about the cluster and maintains the desired state.</p><ul><li><strong>kube-apiserver</strong>: the <strong>front end</strong> of the control plane and the <strong>only component that talks to etcd</strong>. Exposes the Kubernetes REST API; all components and <code>kubectl</code> communicate through it. Handles authn, authz, and admission control. It is stateless and horizontally scalable.</li><li><strong>etcd</strong>: distributed, consistent <strong>key-value store</strong> that is the cluster's <strong>single source of truth</strong> (all cluster state/config). Should be <strong>backed up</strong>; loss of etcd = loss of cluster state.</li><li><strong>kube-scheduler</strong>: watches for <strong>unscheduled Pods</strong> and <strong>assigns each to a node</strong> based on resource requests, affinity/anti-affinity, taints/tolerations, and constraints. It decides placement; it does not start the Pod.</li><li><strong>kube-controller-manager</strong>: runs the <strong>controllers</strong> that drive actual state toward desired state via reconciliation loops (Node, ReplicaSet, Deployment, Job, EndpointSlice controllers, etc.).</li><li><strong>cloud-controller-manager</strong>: integrates with the <strong>cloud provider</strong> — manages cloud load balancers, nodes, and routes. Decouples cloud-specific logic from core Kubernetes.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Only the <strong>API server reads/writes etcd</strong>; everything goes through the API server.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Scheduler <strong>chooses</strong> the node; the <strong>kubelet</strong> on that node actually runs the Pod.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Kubernetes is built on the <strong>reconciliation loop</strong>: observe → diff desired vs actual → act.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-8", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node components (kubelet, kube-proxy, container runtime)", "title": "Node Components", "html": "<p><strong>Node (worker) components</strong> run on every node and keep Pods running and networked.</p><ul><li><strong>kubelet</strong>: the <strong>node agent</strong>. Registers the node, receives Pod specs from the API server, and ensures the described containers are <strong>running and healthy</strong>. It runs <strong>probes</strong> and reports node/Pod status back. It manages Pods, <strong>not</strong> containers it didn't create.</li><li><strong>kube-proxy</strong>: maintains <strong>network rules</strong> on each node to implement <strong>Services</strong>, enabling traffic forwarding and load balancing to backend Pods. Uses iptables or IPVS (or eBPF via some CNIs). It is a per-node network proxy, optional if the CNI handles Service routing.</li><li><strong>Container runtime</strong>: actually <strong>runs the containers</strong> (e.g., <strong>containerd</strong>, <strong>CRI-O</strong>). Kubelet talks to it via the <strong>CRI</strong>.</li></ul><ul><li>Networking on nodes is provided by a <strong>CNI plugin</strong> (e.g., Calico, Cilium, Flannel), which assigns Pod IPs and enables pod-to-pod connectivity.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> kubelet ↔ Pods/health; kube-proxy ↔ Service networking; runtime ↔ runs containers.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> The kubelet does <strong>not</strong> manage the network or implement Services — that's kube-proxy/CNI.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Every node runs kubelet, kube-proxy, and a container runtime; control-plane nodes also run control-plane components.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-9", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "The Kubernetes API and declarative object management with kubectl", "title": "The Kubernetes API and Declarative Management with kubectl", "html": "<p>Kubernetes is <strong>declarative</strong> and <strong>API-centric</strong>: you describe desired state, and controllers continuously reconcile toward it.</p><ul><li><strong>kube-apiserver</strong> exposes a RESTful API; every object has a <strong>spec</strong> (desired state) and <strong>status</strong> (current state, set by the system).</li><li>Objects are grouped into <strong>API groups</strong> and <strong>versions</strong> (e.g., <code>apps/v1</code>, <code>v1</code> core). Manifests declare <code>apiVersion</code>, <code>kind</code>, <code>metadata</code>, and <code>spec</code>.</li><li><strong>Declarative management</strong>: <code>kubectl apply -f file.yaml</code> declares desired state; Kubernetes computes and makes the changes. Preferred for GitOps/version control.</li><li><strong>Imperative management</strong>: commands like <code>kubectl create</code>, <code>run</code>, <code>delete</code>, <code>scale</code> act directly — good for quick tasks but harder to track.</li></ul><p><strong>Common kubectl commands</strong>:</p><ul><li><code>kubectl get</code> / <code>describe</code> — inspect objects.</li><li><code>kubectl apply -f</code> — declarative create/update.</li><li><code>kubectl logs</code>, <code>kubectl exec</code> — debug containers.</li><li><code>kubectl explain</code> — discover field schemas.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>CRDs (CustomResourceDefinitions)</strong> extend the API with new object kinds, often paired with <strong>operators</strong> (custom controllers).</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Prefer <code>apply</code> (declarative) over imperative commands for reproducibility.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> You set <strong>spec</strong>; the system manages <strong>status</strong>. Controllers reconcile spec → status.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-10", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling (nodeSelector, affinity/anti-affinity, taints and tolerations, resource requests and limits)", "title": "Scheduling: Placement Controls and Resources", "html": "<p>The <strong>kube-scheduler</strong> places Pods on nodes; several mechanisms influence or constrain where Pods land.</p><ul><li><strong>Resource requests</strong>: the minimum CPU/memory a Pod needs; used by the scheduler to find a node with enough capacity (drives placement). Unschedulable if no node fits.</li><li><strong>Resource limits</strong>: the maximum a container may use. Exceeding a <strong>memory</strong> limit causes <strong>OOMKill</strong>; CPU over-limit is <strong>throttled</strong>.</li><li><strong>nodeSelector</strong>: simplest constraint — schedule only on nodes with matching <strong>labels</strong>.</li><li><strong>Affinity / anti-affinity</strong>: more expressive rules. <strong>Node affinity</strong> attracts Pods to labeled nodes; <strong>Pod affinity</strong> co-locates Pods; <strong>Pod anti-affinity</strong> spreads them apart. Modes: <strong>requiredDuringScheduling</strong> (hard) vs <strong>preferredDuringScheduling</strong> (soft).</li><li><strong>Taints and tolerations</strong>: a <strong>taint</strong> on a node <strong>repels</strong> Pods; a Pod needs a matching <strong>toleration</strong> to be scheduled there. Effects: <code>NoSchedule</code>, <code>PreferNoSchedule</code>, <code>NoExecute</code> (evicts existing Pods).</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Taints/tolerations are about <strong>nodes repelling Pods</strong> (opt-out); affinity is about <strong>Pods being attracted</strong> (opt-in). A toleration only <strong>allows</strong>, it doesn't force placement.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Requests affect <strong>scheduling</strong>; limits affect <strong>runtime enforcement</strong>. QoS classes (<strong>Guaranteed, Burstable, BestEffort</strong>) derive from requests/limits.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-11", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage basics (Volumes, PersistentVolumes, PersistentVolumeClaims)", "title": "Storage: Volumes, PVs and PVCs", "html": "<p>Kubernetes storage decouples data lifetime from the ephemeral container, with abstractions for persistence and provisioning.</p><ul><li><strong>Volumes</strong>: attached to a <strong>Pod</strong>; they outlive container restarts but are <strong>tied to the Pod's lifecycle</strong> (e.g., <code>emptyDir</code> is deleted when the Pod is removed). Shared among containers in the Pod.</li><li><strong>PersistentVolume (PV)</strong>: a <strong>cluster-scoped</strong> piece of storage provisioned by an admin or dynamically. Its lifecycle is <strong>independent of any Pod</strong>.</li><li><strong>PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)</strong>: a <strong>namespaced</strong> user request for storage (size + access mode). Kubernetes <strong>binds</strong> the PVC to a matching PV; the Pod mounts the PVC.</li><li><strong>StorageClass</strong>: enables <strong>dynamic provisioning</strong> — a PVC referencing a StorageClass auto-creates a PV via a provisioner (often a <strong>CSI driver</strong>).</li></ul><p><strong>Access modes</strong>: <code>ReadWriteOnce</code> (one node), <code>ReadOnlyMany</code>, <code>ReadWriteMany</code>, <code>ReadWriteOncePod</code>.</p><ul><li><strong>Reclaim policy</strong>: <code>Retain</code> (keep data), <code>Delete</code> (remove backing storage). Default for dynamic PVs is often Delete.</li><li><strong>CSI (Container Storage Interface)</strong>: standard for plugging external storage systems into Kubernetes.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> PVCs <strong>request</strong> storage; PVs <strong>provide</strong> it; StorageClass <strong>dynamically provisions</strong> PVs. PV = cluster-scoped, PVC = namespaced.</li></ul>"}, {"id": "fundamentals-note-12", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Other workloads (StatefulSets, DaemonSets, Jobs, CronJobs)", "title": "Workload Controllers: StatefulSets, DaemonSets, Jobs, CronJobs", "html": "<p>Beyond Deployments, Kubernetes offers specialized controllers for different workload patterns.</p><ul><li><strong>StatefulSet</strong>: manages <strong>stateful</strong> applications needing <strong>stable identity</strong>. Provides <strong>stable, ordered Pod names</strong> (<code>web-0</code>, <code>web-1</code>), <strong>stable network IDs</strong>, and <strong>persistent per-Pod storage</strong> (via volumeClaimTemplates). Pods are created/scaled/deleted in <strong>order</strong>. Used for databases, clustered apps (e.g., Kafka, Cassandra).</li><li><strong>DaemonSet</strong>: ensures a copy of a Pod runs on <strong>every node</strong> (or a subset). Ideal for <strong>node-level agents</strong>: log collectors, monitoring agents, CNI/network plugins, storage daemons. New nodes automatically get the Pod.</li><li><strong>Job</strong>: runs Pods to <strong>completion</strong> for batch/one-off tasks. Retries on failure and tracks successful completions (<code>completions</code>, <code>parallelism</code>). Pods are not restarted indefinitely.</li><li><strong>CronJob</strong>: creates <strong>Jobs on a time schedule</strong> using cron syntax (e.g., backups, reports). It's a scheduled wrapper around Jobs.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Deployment = stateless; <strong>StatefulSet = stateful with stable identity/storage</strong>; DaemonSet = one per node; Job = run to completion; CronJob = scheduled Job.</li><li><strong>Exam tip:</strong> Only StatefulSet gives <strong>ordered, stable network and storage identity</strong>; DaemonSet's defining trait is <strong>one Pod per node</strong>.</li></ul>"}], "flashcards": [{"id": "fundamentals-fc-1", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers and images", "front": "What is the OCI (Open Container Initiative)?", "back": "An open governance project under the Linux Foundation that defines industry standards for containers, primarily the Image Specification (image format) and Runtime Specification (how to run a container). It ensures interoperability across tools and runtimes."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-2", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers and images", "front": "What are container image layers and how are they stored?", "back": "An image is built from stacked, read-only filesystem layers, each representing a change (e.g., a Dockerfile instruction). Layers are content-addressable and shared/cached across images, so common layers are downloaded and stored only once."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-3", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers and images", "front": "What is a container registry?", "back": "A service that stores and distributes container images (e.g., Docker Hub, Quay, GHCR, ECR). Clients push images to and pull them from a registry; images are referenced by name and tag or by digest."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-4", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers and images", "front": "What is a container runtime and what role does CRI play?", "back": "A runtime starts and manages containers from images. Kubernetes talks to runtimes (e.g., containerd, CRI-O) through the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), a standard gRPC API the kubelet uses."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-5", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers and images", "front": "Difference between a container image and a running container?", "back": "An image is a static, read-only template (layers + metadata). A container is a running (or runnable) instance of that image, adding a thin writable layer on top for runtime changes."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-6", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and the pod lifecycle", "front": "What is a Pod in Kubernetes?", "back": "The smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes. A Pod is one or more containers that share the same network namespace (IP and ports) and storage volumes, and are scheduled together on a single node."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-7", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and the pod lifecycle", "front": "List the Pod lifecycle phases.", "back": "Pending, Running, Succeeded, Failed, and Unknown. Pending means accepted but not all containers are running yet; Succeeded/Failed are terminal states for all containers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-8", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and the pod lifecycle", "front": "What is an init container?", "back": "A container that runs to completion before the app (regular) containers start. Init containers run sequentially and are used for setup tasks like waiting on dependencies or preparing data."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-9", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and the pod lifecycle", "front": "What are the three container probe types?", "back": "Liveness (restart container if it fails), Readiness (remove Pod from Service endpoints until it passes), and Startup (gives slow-starting apps time before liveness/readiness apply)."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-10", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and the pod lifecycle", "front": "What does a Pod's restartPolicy control, and what are the options?", "back": "It controls whether containers are restarted by the kubelet. Options are Always (default), OnFailure, and Never. It applies to all containers in the Pod."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-11", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and rolling updates", "front": "What does a Deployment do?", "back": "A Deployment provides declarative updates for Pods and ReplicaSets. It manages stateless workloads, handling rollouts, rollbacks, and scaling by creating and managing ReplicaSets."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-12", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and rolling updates", "front": "What is a ReplicaSet's job?", "back": "A ReplicaSet ensures a specified number of identical Pod replicas are running at all times, creating or deleting Pods to match the desired replica count. It is usually managed by a Deployment, not directly."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-13", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and rolling updates", "front": "How does a RollingUpdate deployment strategy work?", "back": "It gradually replaces old Pods with new ones, controlled by maxSurge (extra Pods allowed above desired) and maxUnavailable (Pods allowed to be down). This enables zero-downtime updates."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-14", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and rolling updates", "front": "How do you roll back a Deployment?", "back": "Use 'kubectl rollout undo deployment/<name>'. Deployments keep a revision history of previous ReplicaSets, allowing rollback to a prior revision."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-15", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Deployments, ReplicaSets and rolling updates", "front": "What is the difference between RollingUpdate and Recreate strategies?", "back": "RollingUpdate (default) incrementally replaces Pods for zero downtime. Recreate terminates all existing Pods before creating new ones, causing downtime but ensuring no two versions run simultaneously."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-16", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services and basic networking", "front": "What is a Kubernetes Service?", "back": "An abstraction that defines a stable network endpoint (virtual IP and DNS name) for a logical set of Pods selected by labels, load-balancing traffic across them even as Pods come and go."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-17", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services and basic networking", "front": "What is a ClusterIP Service?", "back": "The default Service type. It exposes the Service on an internal cluster-only virtual IP, reachable only from within the cluster. Used for internal communication between workloads."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-18", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services and basic networking", "front": "What is a NodePort Service?", "back": "Exposes the Service on a static port (default range 30000-32767) on every node's IP. External traffic to <NodeIP>:<NodePort> is routed to the Service. It builds on ClusterIP."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-19", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services and basic networking", "front": "What is a LoadBalancer Service?", "back": "Exposes the Service externally using a cloud provider's external load balancer, which routes to the NodePort/ClusterIP. It is the standard way to expose services publicly in cloud environments."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-20", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services and basic networking", "front": "What provides cluster DNS and how are Services resolved?", "back": "CoreDNS (the default DNS server) provides in-cluster DNS. Services get a record like <service>.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local, letting Pods reach Services by name."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-21", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "front": "What is a ConfigMap?", "back": "An API object that stores non-confidential configuration data as key-value pairs. It can be consumed by Pods as environment variables, command-line args, or mounted files, decoupling config from images."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-22", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "front": "What is a Secret and how is it stored by default?", "back": "A Secret stores sensitive data (passwords, tokens, keys). By default its data is only base64-encoded (not encrypted) in etcd; encryption at rest must be enabled separately. It is consumed like a ConfigMap."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-23", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "front": "Is base64 encoding the same as encryption for Secrets?", "back": "No. Base64 is reversible encoding, not encryption, and provides no real security. Genuine protection requires enabling etcd encryption at rest and proper RBAC."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-24", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "front": "Name two ways a Pod can consume a ConfigMap or Secret.", "back": "As environment variables injected into containers, or as files mounted via a volume. Secrets can also be used as imagePullSecrets for registry authentication."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-25", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces, labels, selectors and annotations", "front": "What is a Namespace?", "back": "A virtual cluster that provides a scope for names and a way to divide cluster resources among users/teams. It enables isolation and resource quotas. Some objects (like nodes) are cluster-scoped and not namespaced."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-26", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces, labels, selectors and annotations", "front": "What are the default namespaces in a cluster?", "back": "default (for user objects with no namespace), kube-system (control plane and system components), kube-public (readable by all, often cluster info), and kube-node-lease (node heartbeat lease objects)."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-27", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces, labels, selectors and annotations", "front": "What is the difference between labels and annotations?", "back": "Labels are key-value pairs used to identify and select objects (queryable via selectors). Annotations attach arbitrary non-identifying metadata (not used for selection), often for tools and libraries."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-28", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces, labels, selectors and annotations", "front": "What are selectors used for?", "back": "Selectors filter objects by their labels. Services, Deployments, and ReplicaSets use label selectors to determine which Pods they manage or route to (e.g., 'app=nginx')."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-29", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control plane components", "front": "What is the kube-apiserver?", "back": "The front end of the control plane and the only component that talks to etcd. It exposes the Kubernetes REST API, validates and processes requests, and serves as the central hub all other components communicate through."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-30", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control plane components", "front": "What is etcd's role?", "back": "etcd is the consistent, highly-available distributed key-value store that holds all cluster state and configuration. It is the cluster's single source of truth and should be backed up."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-31", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control plane components", "front": "What does the kube-scheduler do?", "back": "It watches for newly created Pods with no assigned node and selects an appropriate node for them based on resource requirements, constraints (affinity, taints), and policies."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-32", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control plane components", "front": "What is the kube-controller-manager?", "back": "A control plane component that runs controller processes (e.g., Node, ReplicaSet, Job, EndpointSlice controllers) which watch cluster state and work to drive it toward the desired state."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-33", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control plane components", "front": "What does the cloud-controller-manager do?", "back": "It runs controllers that integrate with the underlying cloud provider's API, managing cloud-specific logic like load balancers, nodes, and routes, keeping cloud-dependent code separate from the core."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-34", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node components", "front": "What is the kubelet?", "back": "The primary node agent that runs on every node. It registers the node, watches the API server for Pods assigned to it, and ensures the containers described in PodSpecs are running and healthy via the CRI."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-35", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node components", "front": "What does kube-proxy do?", "back": "A network proxy running on each node that maintains network rules (using iptables or IPVS) to implement Service abstraction, routing traffic to the correct backend Pods."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-36", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node components", "front": "What is the container runtime's role on a node?", "back": "It is the software responsible for pulling images and running containers (e.g., containerd, CRI-O). The kubelet uses it through the CRI to manage container lifecycle."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-37", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node components", "front": "Which node component handles Pod-to-Pod load balancing for Services?", "back": "kube-proxy. It programs the node's networking rules so traffic to a Service's virtual IP is distributed across the Service's backend Pods."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-38", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "The Kubernetes API and declarative object management", "front": "What is declarative object management with kubectl?", "back": "You describe the desired state in manifest files and apply them with 'kubectl apply -f', letting Kubernetes reconcile actual state to match. This contrasts with imperative commands like 'kubectl create' or 'kubectl run'."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-39", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "The Kubernetes API and declarative object management", "front": "What are the four required top-level fields in most Kubernetes manifests?", "back": "apiVersion, kind, metadata, and spec. The cluster fills in status to report the observed state of the object."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-40", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "The Kubernetes API and declarative object management", "front": "What does the Kubernetes controller reconciliation loop do?", "back": "Controllers continuously compare the desired state (spec) against the actual state (status) and take actions to converge them. This control loop is the foundation of Kubernetes' self-healing behavior."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-41", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "The Kubernetes API and declarative object management", "front": "What is a CustomResourceDefinition (CRD)?", "back": "A CRD extends the Kubernetes API by defining new custom resource types, which can then be managed declaratively with kubectl just like built-in objects. CRDs are the basis of the Operator pattern."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-42", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "front": "What is a nodeSelector?", "back": "The simplest scheduling constraint: a Pod field specifying key-value labels a node must have for the Pod to be scheduled there. The Pod will only run on nodes matching all specified labels."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-43", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "front": "What is the difference between node affinity and pod (anti-)affinity?", "back": "Node affinity attracts Pods to nodes based on node labels (more expressive than nodeSelector). Pod affinity/anti-affinity schedules Pods relative to other Pods' labels, co-locating or spreading them apart."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-44", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "front": "How do taints and tolerations work together?", "back": "A taint on a node repels Pods that do not tolerate it. A toleration on a Pod allows (but does not require) it to be scheduled onto a node with a matching taint. Together they keep unwanted Pods off specific nodes."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-45", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "front": "What is the difference between a resource request and a limit?", "back": "A request is the amount of CPU/memory guaranteed and used by the scheduler to place a Pod. A limit is the maximum a container may use; exceeding a memory limit causes an OOM kill, and CPU above the limit is throttled."}, {"id": "fundamentals-fc-46", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Other workloads", "front": "What is a StatefulSet and how does it differ from a Deployment?", "back": "A StatefulSet manages stateful applications, providing stable, unique network identities, ordered deployment/scaling, and stable persistent storage per Pod. Unlike Deployments, Pods are not interchangeable and have ordinal names (e.g., web-0, web-1)."}], "questions": [{"id": "fundamentals-q-1", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What does the acronym OCI stand for in the context of cloud native containers?", "options": ["Open Container Initiative", "Open Cloud Infrastructure", "Orchestrated Container Interface", "Official Container Image"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "OCI stands for the Open Container Initiative, a Linux Foundation project that defines open standards for container image format, runtime, and distribution. The other expansions are not real organizations or standards."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-2", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "A container image is best described as which of the following?", "options": ["A read-only template containing the application code, runtime, libraries, and dependencies needed to run a container", "A running process with its own isolated network and filesystem namespaces", "A lightweight virtual machine that includes its own guest operating system kernel", "A configuration file that tells Kubernetes how many replicas of a Pod to run"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "An image is a static, read-only package of code and dependencies; a container is the running instance of that image. Containers share the host kernel rather than bundling their own, which distinguishes them from virtual machines."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-3", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Container images are composed of layers. Which statement about image layers is correct?", "options": ["Each layer represents a set of filesystem changes and is read-only, while a writable layer is added on top when a container runs", "Each layer is fully writable, allowing the running container to permanently modify the base image", "Layers must be rebuilt from scratch every time and cannot be shared between images", "An image can contain at most one layer to keep it lightweight"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Image layers are read-only and stacked; when a container starts, a thin writable layer is added on top for runtime changes. Layers are content-addressable and can be cached and shared across images, which is why distinct images sharing a base reuse layers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-4", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the primary purpose of a container registry such as Docker Hub or a private Harbor instance?", "options": ["To store and distribute container images so they can be pushed by builders and pulled by runtimes", "To schedule Pods onto worker nodes based on resource requests", "To provide the writable layer that a container uses at runtime", "To act as the container runtime that executes images on each node"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A registry is a storage and distribution service for images; builders push images to it and nodes pull from it. Scheduling is the kube-scheduler's job, and executing containers is the runtime's job, not the registry's."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-5", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Kubernetes communicates with the container runtime on each node through which standardized interface?", "options": ["CRI (Container Runtime Interface)", "CNI (Container Network Interface)", "CSI (Container Storage Interface)", "OCI (Open Container Initiative) runtime spec"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The kubelet talks to the container runtime via the CRI (Container Runtime Interface). CNI handles networking and CSI handles storage, while the OCI runtime spec is a lower-level standard the runtimes themselves implement rather than the interface Kubernetes uses."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-6", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Since Kubernetes removed the dockershim, which of the following is a commonly used CRI-compatible container runtime in clusters today?", "options": ["containerd", "kube-proxy", "etcd", "kubelet"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "containerd (and CRI-O) are CRI-compatible runtimes widely used after dockershim's removal in Kubernetes 1.24. kube-proxy handles Service networking, etcd is the cluster datastore, and kubelet is the node agent that calls the runtime, not a runtime itself."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-7", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In an image reference like 'nginx:1.25', what does the part after the colon ('1.25') represent?", "options": ["The image tag, which identifies a specific version or variant of the image", "The registry hostname where the image is stored", "The unique content digest of the image manifest", "The number of layers contained in the image"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The portion after the colon is the tag, a human-readable label (often a version) for an image. The registry host appears before the repository name, and the immutable content digest is a SHA-256 hash referenced with '@sha256:...'."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-8", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A team wants to ensure that a Pod always runs the exact same image bits, even if someone overwrites a tag in the registry. What is the most reliable way to reference the image?", "options": ["Pin the image by its immutable content digest (e.g., image@sha256:...)", "Use the 'latest' tag so Kubernetes always fetches the newest build", "Set imagePullPolicy to Never so the node keeps its cached copy", "Reference the image by a semantic version tag such as ':v1.2.3'"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A digest (image@sha256:...) is content-addressable and immutable, so it always resolves to identical bits regardless of tag changes. Tags (including version tags) can be re-pushed to point at different content, and 'latest' is especially mutable; imagePullPolicy: Never only affects caching, not which content a tag maps to."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-9", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Containers & Images", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "CRI-O and containerd both rely on a lower-level component to actually create and run the container process according to the OCI runtime spec. Which component is that?", "options": ["runc, the OCI reference runtime", "kubelet, the node agent", "the Docker daemon (dockerd)", "the kube-apiserver"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Both containerd and CRI-O delegate the actual spawning of the container process to a low-level OCI runtime, most commonly runc. The kubelet and kube-apiserver are Kubernetes control-plane/node components, and dockerd is a higher-level engine that itself historically used runc."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-10", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In Kubernetes, what is the smallest deployable unit that can be created and managed?", "options": ["A container", "A Pod", "A Node", "A Deployment"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes. Containers are not scheduled directly; they always run inside a Pod, which is what the scheduler places onto a Node."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-11", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which of the following best describes the relationship between Pods and containers?", "options": ["A Pod can contain one or more containers that share networking and storage", "A Pod always contains exactly one container", "A container can hold multiple Pods", "Pods and containers are two names for the same object"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Pod can wrap one or more tightly coupled containers that share the same network namespace (IP and port space) and can share storage volumes. Single-container Pods are most common, but multi-container Pods are fully supported."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-12", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Pod phase indicates that the Pod has been accepted by the cluster but one or more of its containers has not yet been created or started?", "options": ["Running", "Pending", "Succeeded", "Failed"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The Pending phase means the Pod was accepted by the API server but is not yet fully running, often because it is waiting to be scheduled or for container images to be pulled. Running means it is bound to a node and at least one container is active."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-13", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the purpose of a (standard) init container in a Pod?", "options": ["It runs alongside the main containers for the entire life of the Pod", "It runs and must complete successfully before the Pod's regular (app) containers start", "It restarts the Pod whenever a main container crashes", "It provides a sidecar proxy for service mesh traffic"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Standard init containers run to completion sequentially before any app containers start, making them useful for setup tasks like waiting on a dependency or preparing data. A container that runs for the Pod's whole life is a regular or native sidecar container (the latter being an init container with restartPolicy: Always), not a standard init container."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-14", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "By default, what happens to a Pod's data stored only inside a container's writable layer when that container restarts?", "options": ["It is preserved automatically by the kubelet", "It is replicated to other Pods", "It is lost, because the container filesystem is ephemeral", "It is moved to the Node's persistent disk"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A container's writable layer is ephemeral, so data written there is lost when the container restarts (the kubelet starts a fresh container from the image). To persist data beyond the container lifecycle, you must use a Volume (for example a PersistentVolume)."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-15", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which kubectl command would you typically use first to view a Pod's events and current state when troubleshooting why it is not starting?", "options": ["kubectl apply -f <file>", "kubectl describe pod <name>", "kubectl edit pod <name>", "kubectl scale pod <name>"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "kubectl describe pod shows detailed status, conditions, and the events stream (such as image pull or scheduling failures), making it the go-to first step for troubleshooting. kubectl apply -f and kubectl edit modify objects rather than inspect them, and kubectl scale targets controllers (like Deployments), not bare Pods."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-16", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which type of probe does the kubelet use to decide whether a container should receive traffic from a Service?", "options": ["Liveness probe", "Readiness probe", "Startup probe", "Health probe"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The readiness probe determines whether a container is ready to serve requests; if it fails, the Pod's IP is removed from the Service's endpoints. A liveness probe instead decides whether to restart a container, a startup probe gates the other probes while a slow app initializes, and there is no probe type called a 'health probe' in Kubernetes."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-17", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Pod is created directly (a bare Pod, not managed by a controller) and runs on a Node. If that Node fails permanently, what happens to the Pod?", "options": ["The scheduler automatically recreates it on a healthy Node", "It is rescheduled by the ReplicaSet that owns it", "It is not recreated on another Node, because no controller is managing its desired state", "The kubelet migrates it live to another Node"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "Bare Pods are not self-healing: a Pod lost with its failed Node is eventually marked for deletion but is never recreated elsewhere, because nothing tracks a desired replica count for it. Rescheduling onto a new Node requires a controller such as a Deployment or ReplicaSet that maintains the desired number of replicas."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-18", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Pods and Lifecycle", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Pod completed a batch task: all of its containers exited with status 0 and will not be restarted. Which terminal Pod phase reflects this outcome?", "options": ["Running", "Succeeded", "Failed", "Unknown"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Succeeded is the terminal phase when all containers in the Pod have terminated successfully (exit code 0) and will not be restarted, which is typical for Job-style workloads. Failed would apply if at least one container terminated with an error, and Unknown indicates the Pod's state could not be obtained (for example, a communication failure with the node)."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-19", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Workloads & Controllers", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary responsibility of a ReplicaSet in Kubernetes?", "options": ["To ensure a specified number of identical Pod replicas are running at any given time", "To expose a set of Pods as a single network service with a stable IP", "To schedule exactly one Pod per node in the cluster", "To store configuration data that Pods consume as environment variables"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A ReplicaSet's job is to maintain a stable set of replica Pods, replacing any that fail or are deleted to match the desired count. Exposing Pods behind a stable IP is the role of a Service, running one Pod per node is the role of a DaemonSet, and storing configuration data is the role of a ConfigMap."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-20", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Workloads & Controllers", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which workload resource is recommended for managing stateless applications and adds declarative rolling-update and rollback capabilities on top of ReplicaSets?", "options": ["StatefulSet", "Deployment", "DaemonSet", "Job"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A Deployment manages stateless apps and provides declarative updates, including rolling updates and rollbacks, by creating and controlling ReplicaSets underneath. StatefulSets target stateful apps needing stable identity, DaemonSets run a Pod on every node, and Jobs run Pods to completion."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-21", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Workloads & Controllers", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "How does a Deployment relate to ReplicaSets and Pods?", "options": ["A Deployment directly creates and manages Pods without any ReplicaSet", "A Deployment manages ReplicaSets, which in turn manage the Pods", "A ReplicaSet manages Deployments, which in turn manage Pods", "Pods manage ReplicaSets, which are grouped into a Deployment"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The ownership hierarchy is Deployment -> ReplicaSet -> Pod. The Deployment creates and updates ReplicaSets, and each ReplicaSet ensures its Pods are running."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-22", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Rolling Updates", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the default update strategy for a Deployment, and what does it do?", "options": ["Recreate, which terminates all old Pods before creating new ones", "RollingUpdate, which gradually replaces old Pods with new ones to avoid downtime", "BlueGreen, which runs two full environments and switches traffic instantly", "Canary, which routes a fixed 10% of traffic to new Pods first"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "RollingUpdate is the default strategy; it incrementally replaces old Pods with new ones so the application stays available. Recreate is the only other built-in strategy but is not the default, and BlueGreen/Canary are not native Deployment strategy types (they are achieved with additional tooling)."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-23", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Rolling Updates", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "During a rolling update, which two parameters control how many Pods can be unavailable and how many extra Pods can be created above the desired count?", "options": ["minReadySeconds and progressDeadlineSeconds", "maxUnavailable and maxSurge", "replicas and revisionHistoryLimit", "terminationGracePeriodSeconds and backoffLimit"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "maxUnavailable caps how many Pods can be down during the update, and maxSurge caps how many Pods can exist above the desired replica count. The other options control readiness/progress timing, history retention, and termination behavior, not the surge and availability of a rolling update."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-24", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Rollouts & Rollback", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A new application version has a bug and you need to return a Deployment to its previously working version. Which kubectl command accomplishes this?", "options": ["kubectl rollout undo deployment/<name>", "kubectl delete replicaset <name> --cascade", "kubectl scale deployment/<name> --replicas=0", "kubectl apply --prune deployment/<name>"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "kubectl rollout undo reverts a Deployment to a previous revision using its stored rollout history. Deleting a ReplicaSet, scaling to zero, or pruning do not restore the prior working version."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-25", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Rollouts & Rollback", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "After a rolling update completes successfully, what happens to the old ReplicaSet that previously ran the application?", "options": ["It is automatically and immediately deleted from the cluster", "It is scaled down to zero replicas but retained to support rollbacks", "It is converted into the new ReplicaSet by updating its Pod template", "It continues running at full replica count as a hot standby"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The Deployment scales the old ReplicaSet down to zero but keeps it (subject to revisionHistoryLimit) so a rollback is possible. It is not deleted immediately, not mutated into the new one, and not kept running at full scale."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-26", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scaling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which field in a Deployment specification determines how many Pod copies the controller should keep running?", "options": ["spec.replicas", "spec.selector", "spec.template.metadata.labels", "spec.strategy.type"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "spec.replicas declares the desired number of Pod copies. The selector matches Pods to the controller, the template labels identify the Pods, and strategy.type defines the update method, not the count."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-27", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Rolling Updates", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "During a Deployment rolling update, how does Kubernetes typically avoid sending traffic to new Pods before they are able to serve requests?", "options": ["It waits for each new Pod's readiness probe to pass before considering it available", "It always pauses for a fixed 30-second delay after each Pod starts", "It relies on the liveness probe to gate traffic to new Pods", "It sends traffic to all Pods immediately and retries failed requests"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Pod is only counted as available and added to Service endpoints once its readiness probe succeeds, which keeps traffic off Pods that are not yet ready. Liveness probes restart unhealthy containers rather than gate traffic, and there is no fixed mandatory delay."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-28", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Kubernetes Service type is the default and exposes the Service only on an internal IP address reachable from within the cluster?", "options": ["NodePort", "ClusterIP", "LoadBalancer", "ExternalName"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "ClusterIP is the default Service type and provides a stable virtual IP reachable only from inside the cluster. NodePort and LoadBalancer build on top of ClusterIP to add external access."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-29", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary purpose of a Kubernetes Service?", "options": ["To schedule Pods onto specific worker nodes", "To provide a stable network endpoint and load balancing for a set of Pods", "To store configuration data injected into Pods", "To enforce which Pods may communicate with each other"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A Service gives a stable IP and DNS name that load-balances traffic across a dynamic set of Pods (selected via labels), decoupling clients from individual Pod IPs that change. Restricting Pod-to-Pod traffic is the job of NetworkPolicies, not Services."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-30", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A NodePort Service is created without specifying a port number. From which default range will Kubernetes allocate the node port?", "options": ["1-1023", "8000-9000", "30000-32767", "40000-65535"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "By default the NodePort range is 30000-32767. Kubernetes picks a port from this range (configurable via the API server's --service-node-port-range flag) and opens it on every node."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-31", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "In a standard cluster running CoreDNS, what is the fully qualified DNS name used to reach a Service named 'web' in the namespace 'shop'?", "options": ["web.shop.pod.cluster.local", "web.shop.svc.cluster.local", "shop.web.svc.cluster.local", "web.svc.shop.cluster.local"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Service DNS names follow the pattern <service>.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local, so it is web.shop.svc.cluster.local. The 'pod' subdomain is used for Pod A records, not Services."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-32", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "How does a Service determine which Pods it should send traffic to?", "options": ["By matching the Service's label selector against Pod labels", "By listing each Pod's IP address explicitly in the Service spec", "By matching Pods that share the Service's name", "By targeting all Pods scheduled on the same node as the Service"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Service uses a label selector; Pods whose labels match become endpoints of the Service. The control plane maintains the resulting EndpointSlice/Endpoints automatically as Pods come and go."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-33", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Service type is typically used to expose a Service externally by provisioning an external load balancer from a cloud provider?", "options": ["ClusterIP", "NodePort", "LoadBalancer", "ExternalName"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A LoadBalancer Service asks the cloud provider's integration to provision an external load balancer with a public IP that forwards to the Service. In a bare cluster with no cloud integration, it may remain pending without an external IP. NodePort and ClusterIP do not provision a cloud load balancer, and ExternalName just maps the Service to an external DNS name via a CNAME."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-34", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Within a single namespace, how can a Pod reach a Service named 'db' using the shortest valid DNS name?", "options": ["Only by using the full name db.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local", "By using just 'db' because the resolver search domains complete it", "By using the Service's ClusterIP, since short names are not resolvable", "By using 'db.cluster.local' with the namespace omitted"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Pods are configured with DNS search domains (e.g. <namespace>.svc.cluster.local), so a short name like 'db' resolves to the Service in the same namespace. The full FQDN also works but is not required for same-namespace lookups."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-35", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "What distinguishes a headless Service (clusterIP set to None) from a normal ClusterIP Service?", "options": ["It allocates a node port on every node instead of a cluster IP", "It provisions an external cloud load balancer automatically", "It has no virtual cluster IP and DNS returns the individual Pod IPs directly", "It can only be used with StatefulSets and rejects label selectors"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A headless Service (clusterIP: None) is not assigned a virtual IP and does not proxy/load-balance; instead DNS returns the A records of the backing Pods so clients can connect to them directly. It is often used with StatefulSets but is not restricted to them."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-36", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Services & Networking", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A NodePort Service named 'api' has a node port of 30080. How can an external client reach the application?", "options": ["By sending traffic to the Service's ClusterIP on port 30080", "By sending traffic to any node's IP address on port 30080", "By using the Pod IP on port 30080 directly", "By resolving api.svc.cluster.local from outside the cluster"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A NodePort opens the chosen port (30080) on every node, so external clients reach the Service via <NodeIP>:30080. The ClusterIP is internal only, and cluster DNS names are not resolvable from outside the cluster."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-37", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary purpose of a ConfigMap in Kubernetes?", "options": ["To store non-confidential configuration data as key-value pairs that can be consumed by Pods", "To store TLS certificates and encryption keys in encrypted form", "To define the desired number of Pod replicas for a Deployment", "To grant Pods permission to access the Kubernetes API"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A ConfigMap stores non-confidential configuration data as key-value pairs, decoupling configuration from container images. Confidential data belongs in a Secret, replica counts are set on Deployments/ReplicaSets, and API permissions are handled by RBAC and ServiceAccounts."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-38", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "How are the data values in a standard Kubernetes Secret encoded when stored in the object's data field?", "options": ["They are base64-encoded", "They are encrypted with AES-256 by default", "They are stored as SHA-256 hashes", "They are stored as plain, unencoded text"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Values in a Secret's data field are base64-encoded, which is encoding, not encryption, and is trivially reversible. AES encryption at rest in etcd is available but must be explicitly configured; it is not the default."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-39", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which two mechanisms can be used to expose the contents of a ConfigMap to a container?", "options": ["As environment variables and as files mounted via a volume", "Only as command-line arguments passed to the container entrypoint", "As annotations on the Pod and as labels on the namespace", "Only by embedding the values directly in the container image"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "ConfigMap data can be injected as environment variables or mounted as files through a volume. Embedding values in the image is exactly what ConfigMaps are designed to avoid, and annotations/labels are metadata, not a configuration-injection mechanism."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-40", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A developer needs to store a database password used by an application Pod. Which Kubernetes object is the most appropriate choice?", "options": ["A Secret", "A ConfigMap", "A PersistentVolume", "A ResourceQuota"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Secrets are intended for sensitive data such as passwords, tokens, and keys, and Kubernetes treats them with extra care (e.g., they are stored in tmpfs rather than written to node disk when mounted as a volume). A ConfigMap is for non-confidential data, while PersistentVolumes and ResourceQuotas serve unrelated purposes."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-41", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "When a ConfigMap is updated, what happens to a container that consumes it as environment variables?", "options": ["The environment variables keep their original values until the Pod is recreated", "The environment variables update automatically within a few seconds", "The Pod is automatically restarted by Kubernetes to pick up the change", "The container immediately crashes because the configuration is now inconsistent"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Environment variables are injected only at container start, so updating the ConfigMap does not change them in a running Pod; the Pod must be recreated. (Values mounted as files via a volume, by contrast, are eventually updated automatically.)"}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-42", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Why is it considered good practice to use ConfigMaps and Secrets rather than hard-coding configuration into container images?", "options": ["It decouples configuration from the image, so the same image can be reused across environments without rebuilding", "It allows containers to run without any container runtime installed", "It automatically reduces the CPU and memory used by the container", "It is required for a Pod to be scheduled onto any node"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Externalizing configuration lets a single immutable image be promoted across dev, staging, and production by swapping ConfigMaps/Secrets, with no rebuild. It does not affect resource usage, the need for a runtime, or scheduling eligibility."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-43", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement about the scope and reference rules for ConfigMaps and Secrets is correct?", "options": ["A Pod can only reference a ConfigMap or Secret that exists in the same namespace as the Pod", "A Pod can reference any ConfigMap or Secret in the cluster regardless of namespace", "ConfigMaps are namespaced but Secrets are cluster-wide objects", "Both ConfigMaps and Secrets are cluster-scoped and exist only once per cluster"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Both ConfigMaps and Secrets are namespaced objects, and a Pod can only reference those in its own namespace. Neither is cluster-scoped, so cross-namespace references are not allowed."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-44", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Which statement best describes the default security posture of Secrets in a standard Kubernetes cluster?", "options": ["By default Secrets are only base64-encoded in etcd, so encryption at rest must be explicitly configured for them to be stored encrypted", "Secrets are always encrypted at rest in etcd with no additional configuration required", "Secrets are encrypted in etcd but transmitted to nodes in plain text", "Secrets cannot be read by any user once created, even cluster administrators"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Out of the box, Secret data is only base64-encoded in etcd, not encrypted; an administrator must enable encryption at rest (an EncryptionConfiguration) for true encryption. Anyone with sufficient API/etcd access can otherwise decode them."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-45", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "ConfigMaps and Secrets", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "An administrator wants ConfigMap or Secret data to be guaranteed unchanged for the lifetime of the object so that the kubelet stops watching it for updates, reducing API server load. Which feature achieves this?", "options": ["Marking the ConfigMap or Secret as immutable", "Adding the data under a binaryData field instead of data", "Setting a low TTL annotation on the object", "Mounting it as a read-only volume in the Pod"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Setting immutable: true on a ConfigMap or Secret prevents any changes to its data and lets the kubelet stop watching it, improving performance and protecting against accidental updates. A read-only mount only restricts the container's write access, not changes to the object itself, and binaryData/TTL do not provide immutability."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-46", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary purpose of a Namespace in Kubernetes?", "options": ["To provide a mechanism for isolating groups of resources within a single cluster", "To physically isolate workloads onto separate worker nodes", "To encrypt network traffic between Pods", "To define the container image registry used by a cluster"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Namespaces provide a scope for names and a way to divide cluster resources among multiple users or teams within one cluster. They are a logical, not physical, isolation; scheduling onto specific nodes is handled by node selectors, taints, and affinity, not namespaces."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-47", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which of the following Kubernetes objects is NOT scoped to a namespace (i.e., it is cluster-wide)?", "options": ["Node", "Pod", "Service", "ConfigMap"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Nodes are cluster-scoped objects and do not belong to any namespace. Pods, Services, and ConfigMaps are all namespaced resources that live within a specific namespace."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-48", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Namespaces", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "When a Kubernetes object is created without specifying a namespace and no namespace is set in the request, which namespace does it go into by default?", "options": ["default", "kube-system", "kube-public", "kube-node-lease"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Objects created without an explicit namespace are placed in the 'default' namespace. The 'kube-system' namespace is reserved for objects created by the Kubernetes system itself."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-49", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Labels", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which statement best describes labels in Kubernetes?", "options": ["Key-value pairs attached to objects that are intended to be meaningful and used to identify and select groups of objects", "Arbitrary non-identifying metadata used to store large blobs such as build information", "Immutable unique identifiers assigned by the API server that cannot be changed after creation", "Cluster-wide DNS records used to route traffic between Services"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Labels are key-value pairs that are meaningful and relevant to users and are used to organize and select subsets of objects. Non-identifying arbitrary metadata is the role of annotations, and labels are mutable, not immutable identifiers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-50", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Labels and Annotations", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the key difference between labels and annotations?", "options": ["Labels are used to identify and select objects, while annotations hold non-identifying metadata that is not used for selection", "Labels can store arbitrarily large data, while annotations are limited to short selectable values", "Labels are cluster-scoped, while annotations are namespace-scoped", "Annotations are used by selectors, while labels are only for human-readable documentation"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Labels are identifying metadata used by selectors to group objects, whereas annotations attach arbitrary non-identifying metadata (such as tooling info or build details) that cannot be used in selectors. Selectors operate on labels, not annotations."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-51", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Selectors", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "How does a Service typically determine which Pods to route traffic to?", "options": ["Through a label selector that matches the labels on the target Pods", "By referencing each Pod directly by its unique name", "By matching the annotations defined on the target Pods", "By selecting all Pods that share the same node as the Service"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Service uses a label selector to dynamically match the set of Pods whose labels satisfy the selector. Services do not select Pods by name or annotation, and they are not tied to a Pod's node placement."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-52", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Selectors", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a set-based label selector requirement?", "options": ["environment in (production, staging)", "environment = production", "environment == production", "environment != production"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Set-based selectors filter labels by a set of values using operators like 'in', 'notin', and 'exists' (e.g., 'environment in (production, staging)'). The '=', '==', and '!=' forms are equality-based selectors, not set-based."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-53", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Selectors", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Deployment's '.spec.selector.matchLabels' is set to 'app: web'. What must be true for the Deployment to manage its Pods correctly?", "options": ["The Pod template's labels must include 'app: web' so the selector matches the Pods it creates", "The Pods must reside in a different namespace than the Deployment", "The Pod template must omit the 'app' label so the controller can assign it automatically", "The matchLabels selector must use an annotation key rather than a label key"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Deployment's selector must match the labels in its Pod template; otherwise the API rejects it or the controller cannot own its Pods. The Deployment and its Pods live in the same namespace, and selectors operate on labels, not annotations."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-54", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Annotations", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which of the following is the most appropriate use of an annotation rather than a label?", "options": ["Storing a Deployment's last-applied configuration or a tool's build/release information", "Marking Pods as 'tier: frontend' so a Service can select them", "Grouping Pods by 'environment: production' for a label selector query", "Identifying which Pods a ReplicaSet should manage"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Annotations are ideal for attaching non-identifying metadata such as last-applied-configuration, build numbers, or tooling pointers that are never used for selection. The other choices all describe identifying metadata used by selectors, which is the job of labels."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-55", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which control plane component acts as the front end of the Kubernetes control plane, exposing the REST API that all other components and users interact with?", "options": ["kube-scheduler", "kube-apiserver", "etcd", "kubelet"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kube-apiserver exposes the Kubernetes API and is the central hub through which all internal and external communication flows. The kubelet is a node agent (not a control plane component), and etcd is the backing data store, not the API front end."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-56", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary role of etcd in a Kubernetes cluster?", "options": ["It schedules Pods onto worker nodes", "It serves as the consistent, distributed key-value store that holds all cluster state", "It runs the application containers", "It load-balances traffic to Services"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "etcd is a consistent, distributed key-value store that persists all cluster data and configuration, acting as the single source of truth. Scheduling is done by kube-scheduler, and containers run on nodes via the container runtime."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-57", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which control plane component is responsible for assigning newly created Pods that have no node yet to a suitable worker node?", "options": ["kube-controller-manager", "kube-scheduler", "kube-proxy", "cloud-controller-manager"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kube-scheduler watches for Pods with no assigned node and selects an appropriate node based on resource requirements, constraints, affinity rules, and policies. kube-proxy handles Service networking on nodes, not scheduling."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-58", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "The kube-controller-manager runs many controllers as a single process. What is the fundamental job of a controller?", "options": ["To translate YAML manifests into container images", "To continuously reconcile the cluster's actual state toward the desired state declared in the API", "To encrypt secrets stored in etcd", "To authenticate API requests from users"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Controllers implement reconciliation loops that watch the desired state via the API server and take action to drive the actual state to match it. Authentication is handled by the API server, not by controllers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-59", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Why was the cloud-controller-manager introduced as a separate component from the kube-controller-manager?", "options": ["To run application workloads closer to the cloud provider's region", "To decouple cloud-provider-specific control logic from the core Kubernetes code so providers can evolve independently", "To replace etcd with a cloud-managed database", "To schedule Pods only onto cloud-based nodes"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The cloud-controller-manager isolates provider-specific logic (node lifecycle, routes, load balancers) so cloud vendors can maintain their integrations out of the main Kubernetes tree and release on their own schedule. It does not replace etcd or run workloads."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-60", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "In a standard Kubernetes architecture, which statement about how control plane components communicate with etcd is correct?", "options": ["Every component reads and writes directly to etcd", "Only the kube-apiserver talks to etcd directly; other components go through the API server", "The kube-scheduler writes node assignments straight into etcd", "kubelet on each node persists Pod status directly to etcd"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kube-apiserver is the only component that communicates directly with etcd; all other components read and write cluster state through the API server. This centralizes authentication, authorization, validation, and admission control."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-61", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which set of controllers is typically managed by the cloud-controller-manager rather than the kube-controller-manager?", "options": ["Deployment, ReplicaSet, and Job controllers", "Node lifecycle, route, and service (load balancer) controllers", "Namespace and ServiceAccount controllers", "Endpoint and CronJob controllers"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The cloud-controller-manager runs provider-dependent controllers: the node controller (which checks the cloud provider when a node stops responding), the route controller (configuring cloud network routes), and the service controller (provisioning cloud load balancers). Deployment, Job, Namespace, ServiceAccount, Endpoint, and CronJob controllers are provider-agnostic and remain in kube-controller-manager."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-62", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "If etcd in a cluster becomes completely unavailable while the rest of the control plane stays up, what is the most accurate description of the immediate impact?", "options": ["All running Pods on worker nodes are immediately terminated", "Existing workloads keep running, but the API server cannot read or persist cluster state, so changes and reconciliation effectively stall", "The kube-scheduler automatically takes over storing state in memory", "Worker nodes continue to register new Pods normally through kubelet"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Already-running Pods continue executing because the data plane operates independently of the control plane, but with etcd down the API server cannot serve or persist state, so new changes and controller reconciliation cannot proceed. No other component substitutes for etcd as the cluster's state store."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-63", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Control Plane", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "When multiple replicas of kube-controller-manager or kube-scheduler are run for high availability, how do they avoid acting on the same objects simultaneously?", "options": ["They shard objects by namespace, with each replica owning a subset", "They use leader election so only one replica is active at a time while the others stand by", "They run as a single combined process behind a load balancer", "etcd randomly assigns each replica a partition of objects"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "These components use leader election (backed by a Lease object in the API) so that only one active instance performs reconciliation or scheduling at a time, while standby replicas wait to acquire leadership if the current leader fails. They do not shard work across replicas."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-64", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which node component is the primary agent that runs on every node and is responsible for ensuring that the containers described in PodSpecs are running and healthy?", "options": ["kube-proxy", "kubelet", "kube-scheduler", "kube-controller-manager"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kubelet is the node agent that registers the node and ensures the containers in each assigned PodSpec are running and healthy. kube-proxy handles network rules, while kube-scheduler and kube-controller-manager are control-plane components, not node agents."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-65", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the main responsibility of kube-proxy on a worker node?", "options": ["Pulling container images from registries", "Maintaining network rules that allow traffic to reach the correct Pods backing a Service", "Scheduling Pods onto nodes based on resource requests", "Storing the cluster's desired state in a key-value store"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "kube-proxy maintains network rules (e.g., via iptables or IPVS) on each node to implement Service load balancing and forward traffic to the appropriate backend Pods. Image pulling is done by the container runtime, scheduling by kube-scheduler, and state storage by etcd."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-66", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which node component is directly responsible for pulling container images and starting and stopping containers?", "options": ["kubelet", "kube-proxy", "The container runtime", "etcd"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "The container runtime (such as containerd or CRI-O) is responsible for the low-level work of pulling images and running containers. The kubelet instructs the runtime via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI) but does not run containers itself."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-67", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Through which standardized interface does the kubelet communicate with the container runtime?", "options": ["CNI (Container Network Interface)", "CSI (Container Storage Interface)", "CRI (Container Runtime Interface)", "OCI (Open Container Initiative) runtime spec"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "The kubelet talks to the container runtime through the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), a gRPC API. CNI handles networking and CSI handles storage; the OCI spec defines image and runtime formats but is not the kubelet-to-runtime API."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-68", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which set of node components runs on EVERY node in a typical Kubernetes cluster, including control-plane nodes?", "options": ["kube-apiserver and etcd", "kubelet and a container runtime", "kube-scheduler and kube-controller-manager", "cloud-controller-manager and kube-proxy"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Every node, including control-plane nodes, runs a kubelet and a container runtime because all nodes must run Pods (control-plane components themselves often run as Pods). The scheduler, controller-manager, and apiserver are control-plane-only components."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-69", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A new Pod has been scheduled to a node. Which component on that node actually receives the assignment and works with the container runtime to start the Pod's containers?", "options": ["kube-scheduler", "kube-proxy", "kubelet", "kube-controller-manager"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "Once kube-scheduler binds a Pod to a node, the kubelet on that node detects the assignment via the API server and instructs the container runtime to start the containers. The scheduler only decides placement and does not start containers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-70", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best describes the relationship between the kubelet and the container runtime?", "options": ["The kubelet is a plugin that runs inside the container runtime", "The kubelet manages Pods and delegates container lifecycle operations to the container runtime via CRI", "The container runtime schedules Pods and the kubelet runs the containers", "They are two names for the same process"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kubelet manages Pods at the node level and delegates the actual creation and lifecycle of containers to the container runtime through the CRI. They are distinct components, and the kubelet is not embedded within the runtime."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-71", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "After the removal of Docker support (dockershim) in Kubernetes 1.24, which of the following is a commonly used, CRI-compliant container runtime that the kubelet can talk to directly?", "options": ["dockershim", "containerd", "runc only, with no higher-level runtime", "kube-proxy"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "containerd is a CRI-compliant high-level runtime that the kubelet communicates with directly after dockershim was removed in 1.24. dockershim itself was removed, runc is a low-level OCI runtime invoked by containerd rather than the kubelet, and kube-proxy is a networking component, not a runtime."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-72", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Node Components", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "If kube-proxy stops functioning on a node but the kubelet and container runtime keep working, what is the most likely observable effect?", "options": ["Existing Pods on the node are immediately terminated", "New container images can no longer be pulled to the node", "ClusterIP Service routing to Pods on that node may break, even though Pods continue running", "The node is removed from etcd and deregistered from the cluster"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "kube-proxy programs the Service-to-Pod network rules, so its failure breaks Service (e.g., ClusterIP) routing, while Pods themselves keep running because the kubelet and runtime are unaffected. Image pulling is the runtime's job, and node registration is handled by the kubelet, so neither is impacted by kube-proxy failing."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-73", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes API", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "In Kubernetes, what is the central component that clients such as kubectl communicate with to create, read, update, and delete cluster objects?", "options": ["The kube-apiserver", "The kubelet on each node", "The container runtime", "The kube-proxy"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The kube-apiserver is the front end of the control plane and the single entry point for all API requests; kubectl talks to it over REST. The kubelet manages pods on a node and kube-proxy handles networking, neither of which is the API entry point."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-74", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Declarative Management", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which kubectl command is the standard way to apply a declarative configuration so that Kubernetes reconciles the cluster to match the desired state defined in a manifest file?", "options": ["kubectl apply -f", "kubectl run", "kubectl exec", "kubectl describe"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "`kubectl apply -f` is the declarative management command: it creates objects if they do not exist and updates them to match the manifest if they do. `kubectl run` is imperative, `kubectl exec` runs commands in a container, and `kubectl describe` only displays details."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-75", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Imperative vs Declarative", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the key difference between imperative and declarative object management in Kubernetes?", "options": ["Imperative commands tell Kubernetes which operation to perform, while declarative management lets you specify the desired end state and Kubernetes determines the operations", "Imperative management only works on the control plane, while declarative management only works on worker nodes", "Declarative management bypasses the API server, while imperative management uses it", "Imperative management can only create objects, while declarative management can only delete them"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Imperative management (e.g., kubectl create/delete/run) specifies the action to take, whereas declarative management (kubectl apply) specifies the desired state and lets Kubernetes reconcile toward it. Both go through the API server and both can create, update, and delete objects."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-76", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "API Objects", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "When you submit a manifest to the Kubernetes API, which field combination identifies the type of resource being described?", "options": ["apiVersion and kind", "metadata and labels", "spec and status", "name and namespace"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The `apiVersion` and `kind` fields together tell the API server which resource type and API group/version the object belongs to (for example, apps/v1 + Deployment). `metadata` identifies the individual object, while `spec` and `status` describe desired and observed state."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-77", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "API Objects", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "In a typical Kubernetes object, what is the purpose of the 'spec' field versus the 'status' field?", "options": ["'spec' describes the desired state set by the user, and 'status' describes the current observed state maintained by Kubernetes", "'spec' is the observed state, and 'status' is the desired state set by the user", "'spec' stores credentials, and 'status' stores the object's labels", "Both fields are written only by the user and never modified by the control plane"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The user defines the desired state in `spec`, and Kubernetes controllers continuously update `status` to reflect the actual observed state. The control plane writes `status`, not the user, which is the opposite of the reversed distractor."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-78", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "kubectl Basics", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which kubectl command would you use to display detailed information and recent events about a specific running pod for troubleshooting?", "options": ["kubectl describe pod <name>", "kubectl get pod <name>", "kubectl label pod <name>", "kubectl cordon pod <name>"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "`kubectl describe` shows a human-readable summary including the object's recent events, which is commonly used for troubleshooting. `kubectl get` only lists basic status without events, `kubectl label` modifies labels, and `kubectl cordon` applies to nodes, not pods."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-79", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "API Groups and Versioning", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Kubernetes organizes its API into groups (such as the core group and named groups like apps or batch). What is the primary purpose of this API grouping and versioning scheme?", "options": ["It allows the API to evolve independently per group and version, enabling features to progress through alpha, beta, and stable stages", "It encrypts API traffic differently for each group to improve security", "It assigns each API group to a dedicated physical node in the cluster", "It determines which user accounts are allowed to authenticate to the cluster"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "API groups and per-group versions let different parts of the API evolve independently and move through maturity stages (v1alpha1, v1beta1, v1). Grouping is about API organization and evolution, not encryption, node assignment, or authentication."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-80", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Declarative Management", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A team manages a Deployment exclusively with 'kubectl apply'. They want to remove a field they previously set in the manifest, so they delete that field and run 'kubectl apply' again. How does declarative apply handle the removed field?", "options": ["Apply detects the field was removed from the configuration and prunes it from the live object, because it tracks the previously applied configuration", "The field is permanently locked and can never be removed once set", "Apply ignores removed fields entirely, so the old value always remains on the object", "The entire Deployment is deleted and must be recreated from scratch"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "`kubectl apply` records the last-applied configuration (via an annotation or server-side apply field tracking) and uses a three-way merge, so fields removed from the manifest are removed from the live object. It does not lock fields, blindly ignore removals, or delete and recreate the object."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-81", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "kubectl Basics", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "When you run a kubectl command, where does kubectl read the connection details (cluster address, credentials, and context) needed to reach the API server?", "options": ["From a kubeconfig file (by default ~/.kube/config)", "From environment variables that the API server pushes to the client", "From the kubelet running on the local machine", "From a ConfigMap stored inside the cluster"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "kubectl uses a kubeconfig file (default location ~/.kube/config) that holds clusters, users, and contexts to know which API server to contact and how to authenticate. It does not rely on the kubelet, in-cluster ConfigMaps, or server-pushed environment variables for this."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-82", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Kubernetes control plane component is responsible for assigning newly created Pods to suitable Nodes?", "options": ["kubelet", "kube-scheduler", "kube-proxy", "kube-controller-manager"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The kube-scheduler watches for newly created Pods that have no assigned Node and selects a Node for each one to run on. The kubelet runs on each Node and starts the containers once a Pod is bound to that Node, but it does not choose the Node. kube-proxy handles Service networking, and kube-controller-manager runs controllers such as the Deployment and Node controllers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-83", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the simplest way to constrain a Pod so it is only scheduled onto Nodes that carry a specific label, such as disktype=ssd?", "options": ["A taint on the Node", "A nodeSelector in the Pod spec", "A ResourceQuota in the namespace", "A PodDisruptionBudget"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "nodeSelector is the simplest node-constraint mechanism: the Pod is only scheduled onto Nodes whose labels match every key/value pair listed. A taint does the opposite (it repels Pods unless they tolerate it), a ResourceQuota limits aggregate resource consumption in a namespace, and a PodDisruptionBudget limits voluntary disruptions; none of these target node placement by label."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-84", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Taints and tolerations work together to influence scheduling. What is the correct relationship between them?", "options": ["A taint is applied to a Pod, and a matching toleration on a Node lets the Pod run there", "A taint is applied to a Node to repel Pods, and a matching toleration on a Pod allows that Pod to be scheduled there", "Both taints and tolerations are applied to Nodes to attract Pods", "A toleration forces a Pod onto a specific Node regardless of resources"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "Taints are applied to Nodes and repel Pods that do not tolerate them; a Pod must carry a matching toleration to be scheduled onto a tainted Node. A toleration only permits scheduling onto a tainted Node—it does not attract or force a Pod onto any particular Node (node affinity or nodeSelector is used to attract Pods)."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-85", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A Pod specifies a CPU request of 250m and a CPU limit of 500m. What do these two values mean?", "options": ["The Pod is guaranteed 500m and throttled at 250m", "The scheduler reserves 250m on a Node for the Pod, and the container may burst up to 500m before being throttled", "Both values are only advisory and have no effect on scheduling", "The Pod will be evicted if it uses more than 250m"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The request (250m) is what the scheduler uses to reserve capacity and decide whether a Node has room; the limit (500m) is the ceiling enforced by the kubelet at which CPU usage is throttled. CPU is a compressible resource, so exceeding the limit causes throttling rather than eviction or termination."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-86", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the primary purpose of Pod anti-affinity?", "options": ["To keep Pods that match a label selector away from each other, for example spreading replicas across different Nodes", "To attract Pods toward Nodes with the most free memory", "To prevent a Pod from ever being rescheduled after a Node failure", "To guarantee two Pods always land on the same Node"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "Pod anti-affinity expresses that a Pod should NOT be co-located with other Pods matching a label selector within a given topology (such as a Node or zone), commonly used to spread replicas for higher availability. Pod affinity (not anti-affinity) is what co-locates Pods, and neither feature controls rescheduling behavior after a Node failure."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-87", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Node affinity rules can be either requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution or preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution. What distinguishes these two types?", "options": ["'required' is a hard rule that must be met for scheduling, while 'preferred' is a soft rule the scheduler tries to honor but can ignore", "'required' applies only at runtime, while 'preferred' applies only at scheduling time", "'preferred' is a hard rule and 'required' is a soft rule", "Both are hard rules but 'preferred' has higher priority"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A 'required' rule is mandatory—the Pod will not be scheduled unless it is satisfied—whereas a 'preferred' rule is a soft preference that the scheduler weights but can disregard if no matching Node is available. The shared 'IgnoredDuringExecution' suffix means neither type evicts an already-running Pod if Node labels later change."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-88", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Pod sets its memory request equal to its memory limit, and these are the only resources it specifies. Which Quality of Service (QoS) class will Kubernetes assign to this Pod, assuming CPU is also set with request equal to limit?", "options": ["BestEffort", "Burstable", "Guaranteed", "Preemptible"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "When every container in a Pod sets both CPU and memory and the request equals the limit for each, the Pod receives the Guaranteed QoS class, making it the last to be evicted under Node memory pressure. Burstable applies when at least one resource has a request lower than its limit, BestEffort applies when no requests or limits are set, and 'Preemptible' is not a Kubernetes QoS class."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-89", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A Node has a taint with the effect NoSchedule. What does this effect do to Pods that do not tolerate the taint?", "options": ["Existing Pods on the Node are immediately evicted", "New Pods without a matching toleration will not be scheduled onto the Node, but already-running Pods are unaffected", "Pods are scheduled but cannot access the network", "The Node is removed from the cluster"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The NoSchedule effect prevents new Pods lacking a matching toleration from being scheduled onto the Node, but it does not evict Pods that are already running there. The NoExecute effect is the one that also evicts existing intolerant Pods, while PreferNoSchedule is a soft variant that only discourages scheduling."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-90", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Scheduling", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Pod is created with a CPU and memory request that no single Node in the cluster can satisfy. What will happen to the Pod?", "options": ["It will be scheduled anyway and share resources with other Pods", "It will remain in the Pending state until a Node with enough allocatable capacity becomes available", "It will be automatically split across multiple Nodes", "It will be deleted by the scheduler"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "If no Node has enough allocatable capacity to meet the Pod's resource requests, the scheduler cannot bind it and the Pod stays Pending until sufficient capacity appears (for example, via cluster autoscaling or freed resources). A Pod always runs on a single Node and is never split, and the scheduler does not delete unschedulable Pods—it leaves them Pending and records a scheduling event."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-91", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "A container's writable layer is ephemeral, so data written there is lost when the container restarts. Which Kubernetes object is used to give a Pod storage that can persist beyond a single container restart and be shared between containers in the same Pod?", "options": ["A Volume", "A Secret", "A ConfigMap", "A Namespace"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Volume is attached at the Pod level and survives container restarts within that Pod, and it can be mounted into multiple containers in the Pod. Secrets and ConfigMaps inject configuration data, not general-purpose persistent storage, and a Namespace is just a logical grouping mechanism."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-92", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "What is the primary purpose of a PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)?", "options": ["To request storage resources of a certain size and access mode on behalf of a Pod", "To define the underlying storage backend technology (NFS, iSCSI, cloud disk)", "To schedule Pods onto specific nodes that have local disks", "To encrypt data at rest on the cluster's storage"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A PVC is a user's request for storage, specifying attributes like size and access mode, which Kubernetes binds to a matching PersistentVolume. Defining the actual backend is the role of the PersistentVolume (or StorageClass provisioner), not the claim."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-93", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best describes the relationship between a PersistentVolume (PV) and a PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)?", "options": ["A PVC binds to a PV that satisfies its requested capacity and access mode, then Pods reference the PVC", "A PV references a PVC directly, and Pods mount the PV without involving the claim", "PVs and PVCs are interchangeable names for the same object", "A PVC must be created inside a PV's YAML as a nested field"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A PVC is matched and bound to a suitable PV, and Pods then consume the storage by referencing the PVC. The PV is a cluster resource representing actual storage, while the PVC is the consumer's request, and they are distinct objects with a one-to-one binding."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-94", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "What is the main role of a StorageClass in Kubernetes?", "options": ["To enable dynamic provisioning so a PersistentVolume is created automatically when a PVC requests storage", "To define network policies for storage traffic between Pods", "To statically pre-create a fixed pool of PersistentVolumes at cluster install time", "To set the file system permissions inside a mounted volume"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A StorageClass describes a class of storage and ties a PVC to a provisioner that creates a matching PV on demand (dynamic provisioning), removing the need for an administrator to pre-create PVs. It does not handle network policy or filesystem permissions."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-95", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A PVC specifies the access mode ReadWriteOnce (RWO). What does this access mode mean?", "options": ["The volume can be mounted as read-write by a single node", "The volume can be mounted read-write by many nodes simultaneously", "The volume can be read by anyone but written only once", "The volume can only be mounted by Pods in a single namespace"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "ReadWriteOnce allows the volume to be mounted as read-write by a single node, where multiple Pods on that same node may use it. Many-node read-write access corresponds to ReadWriteMany (RWX), restricting access to a single Pod is ReadWriteOncePod, and the access mode is unrelated to namespaces."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-96", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "An application Pod is deleted and recreated, but the data it stored must survive. Which approach correctly ensures the data persists independently of the Pod's lifecycle?", "options": ["Store the data on a PersistentVolume accessed through a PVC", "Store the data in an emptyDir volume", "Store the data in the container's writable layer", "Store the data in a ConfigMap mounted into the Pod"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A PersistentVolume consumed via a PVC has a lifecycle independent of any Pod, so data survives Pod deletion. An emptyDir is tied to the Pod and is deleted with it, the container layer is ephemeral, and ConfigMaps are read-only configuration data, not application-generated persistent state."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-97", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which volume type provides empty scratch space that is created when a Pod is assigned to a node and deleted permanently when that Pod is removed from the node?", "options": ["emptyDir", "persistentVolumeClaim", "nfs", "hostPath"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "An emptyDir volume starts empty when the Pod is scheduled and is deleted forever when the Pod is removed from the node, making it suitable for temporary scratch data. PVC-backed, NFS, and hostPath volumes can outlive the Pod and are not purely ephemeral scratch space."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-98", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A PersistentVolume has its reclaim policy set to Retain. What happens to that PV and its data after the bound PVC is deleted?", "options": ["The PV is released but its data is kept, and the volume is not made available to a new claim until an administrator manually reclaims it", "The PV and its backing storage are automatically deleted along with the data", "The PV is immediately rebound to the next PVC that requests it, keeping the old data", "The PV is scrubbed of data and returned to the Available pool automatically"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "With the Retain reclaim policy, deleting the PVC leaves the PV in a Released state with its data intact, requiring manual administrator action before the storage can be reused. The Delete policy removes the PV and backing storage, while the deprecated Recycle policy scrubbed and reused the volume automatically."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-99", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Storage Basics", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "Which Kubernetes standard defines a common interface that allows storage vendors to write plugins exposing their systems (such as cloud disks or NFS) to Kubernetes for provisioning PersistentVolumes?", "options": ["CSI (Container Storage Interface)", "CRI (Container Runtime Interface)", "CNI (Container Network Interface)", "OCI (Open Container Initiative)"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "The Container Storage Interface (CSI) is the standard that lets storage providers build drivers that integrate their systems with Kubernetes for provisioning and managing volumes. CRI handles container runtimes, CNI handles networking, and OCI standardizes container image and runtime formats."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-100", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which Kubernetes workload controller ensures that a copy of a Pod runs on every node (or a selected subset of nodes) in the cluster?", "options": ["Deployment", "DaemonSet", "StatefulSet", "Job"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A DaemonSet ensures that all (or some) nodes run a copy of a Pod, which is ideal for node-level agents like log collectors or monitoring daemons. A Deployment just maintains a replica count without per-node placement guarantees, a StatefulSet manages ordered stateful Pods, and a Job runs Pods to completion."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-101", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which workload resource is designed to run a task to completion, creating one or more Pods and ensuring a specified number of them successfully terminate?", "options": ["Job", "ReplicaSet", "DaemonSet", "Deployment"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "A Job creates Pods that run until completion and tracks successful completions, making it suitable for batch or one-off tasks. A ReplicaSet and Deployment keep long-running Pods alive indefinitely rather than running to completion, and a DaemonSet runs a Pod per node continuously."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-102", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "easy", "question": "Which workload controller is best suited for running a Job on a repeating time-based schedule?", "options": ["DaemonSet", "StatefulSet", "CronJob", "Deployment"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "A CronJob creates Jobs on a repeating schedule defined by a cron expression, similar to cron on Linux. A DaemonSet, StatefulSet, and Deployment manage long-running Pods and are not time-scheduled controllers."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-103", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Why would you choose a StatefulSet instead of a Deployment to run a clustered database?", "options": ["StatefulSets provide stable, unique network identities and stable persistent storage per Pod", "StatefulSets automatically run a Pod on every node in the cluster", "StatefulSets run their Pods to completion and then stop them", "StatefulSets do not require a container image to be specified"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "StatefulSets give each Pod a stable, ordinal-based identity (a persistent hostname) and stable persistent storage that follows the Pod across rescheduling, which stateful applications like databases need. Deployments treat their Pods as interchangeable and do not guarantee stable identity or storage; running a Pod per node is a DaemonSet, and running to completion is a Job."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-104", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "A CronJob uses a schedule field. What format does this field use?", "options": ["An ISO 8601 timestamp", "A standard cron expression (e.g., \"0 2 * * *\")", "A duration string such as \"24h\"", "A Unix epoch timestamp in seconds"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "A CronJob's schedule field uses standard cron syntax with five fields (minute, hour, day of month, month, day of week), so \"0 2 * * *\" means daily at 2:00 AM. It is not a duration, an ISO 8601 timestamp, or an epoch value."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-105", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "By default (podManagementPolicy: OrderedReady), when a StatefulSet with three replicas is scaled up, in what order are the Pods created?", "options": ["All at once in parallel", "In a random order determined by the scheduler", "Sequentially in ascending ordinal order (pod-0, then pod-1, then pod-2)", "In reverse order, starting from the highest ordinal"], "answerIndex": 2, "explanation": "With the default OrderedReady pod management policy, a StatefulSet creates Pods one at a time in ascending ordinal order, waiting for each to be Running and Ready before starting the next. (Setting podManagementPolicy to Parallel removes this ordering.) Deletion during scale-down happens in reverse ordinal order, and Deployments create Pods in parallel."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-106", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "medium", "question": "Which statement best describes how a typical DaemonSet places Pods when a new node joins the cluster?", "options": ["Nothing changes until an administrator manually edits the DaemonSet", "The DaemonSet controller automatically schedules a Pod onto the new node", "The new node is ignored because DaemonSets only target nodes present at creation time", "A Job is triggered to decide whether the node should run the Pod"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "The DaemonSet controller continuously reconciles state, so when a node is added that matches the DaemonSet's node selection (and tolerations/taints), it automatically schedules a Pod onto that node. Likewise, removing a node garbage-collects its DaemonSet Pod."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-107", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A Job is configured with completions: 5 and parallelism: 2. How does the Job controller behave?", "options": ["It runs exactly one Pod five times in sequence", "It needs 5 successful Pod completions and runs up to 2 Pods at a time", "It runs 5 Pods simultaneously and stops after any 2 complete", "It creates 2 Pods total and considers the Job done when both finish"], "answerIndex": 1, "explanation": "With completions: 5 the Job requires five successful completions, and parallelism: 2 limits it to at most two Pods running concurrently at any time. The Job keeps launching Pods (up to the parallelism limit) until five have completed successfully."}, {"id": "fundamentals-q-108", "domainId": "fundamentals", "topic": "Kubernetes Workloads", "difficulty": "hard", "question": "A CronJob's concurrencyPolicy is set to Forbid. What happens if a new run is scheduled while the previous Job is still running?", "options": ["The new run is skipped because a previous Job is still active", "The previous Job is terminated and replaced by the new run", "Both Jobs run concurrently with no restriction", "The CronJob is automatically suspended until the running Job finishes"], "answerIndex": 0, "explanation": "With concurrencyPolicy: Forbid, the CronJob skips a new scheduled run if the prior Job has not yet finished. \"Replace\" would terminate and replace the running Job, while \"Allow\" (the default) permits concurrent runs; none of these suspend the CronJob."}]});
